column1: COST CURVES for other gas mitigation
the data is from the EPA cost curve spreadsheets -- generated automatically by CCURVES MACRO.xls: make changes there and then rerun the macro
FORMAT: first row of each curve is carbon tax -- second row is percent reduction as if carbon tax was applied using standard
uses 100 yr GWP 's (21 for methane and 310 for N2O) -- changes in GWP do not need to be made here as it is coded into the model
FILE also contains parameters for energy price adjustments to cost curves
Below zero reductions are applied in all scenarios, including base cases (I.e., assumed that these become part of the baseline)
File for run-time adjustment control parameters for the other gases cost curves
mj 11/02 (built from 11-02 ch4 and n2o calib.xls)
first period (1990=2) in which cost curves will have an effect on other gas emissions
number of timesteps in which to pick up below 0 cost curve reductions (value of 2 means 50% appear in first avail period (IBZFIRST), and all in 2nd avail period -- 0 and 1 have the same effect)
Sensitivity to energy prices -- 1 indicates movement directly with gas prices, < 1 indicates less efficient/partial recovery of methane
(approximate conversion of 9.1 GJ CH4 per TCE is used if this parameter is set to 1, otherwise it is proportionally less)
Data Source (11/02 mj):  Plotted representative curves from the EPA spreadsheets, estimated sensitivity to energy prices
Note that sensitivity roughly corresponds to quality of recovered gas/use for resale.  So Gas and Coal have high figures (most recovered gas is resold)
whereas oil (flaring) and landfill (low-quality recovered gas) tend to have less sensitivity to energy prices.  The manure curves tend to be very responsive
for some reason.  All of these have been scaled down slightly together (dampen rapid price changes) in the calib.xls file.

column3: NOTE: Must have correct region and gas/src numbers below (code reads them...)

column1: Get free emissions reductions from cost curves regardless of IOTHGASTOG setting -- IOTHGASTOG controls
the effects of taxes on the other gases/cost curves separately.
0 = no free reductions unless IOTHGASTOG > 0, 1 = always free reductions
